'''Shirahige Shrine''' (しろひげじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} located in {{jalink|Kawashima Kasada-chō|Q131938355}}, {{jalink|Kakamigahara City|Q641491}}, {{jalink|Gifu Prefecture|Q131277}} ({{jalink|Shirahige Shrine|Q705303}}). Under the {{jalink|Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|shrine ranking system}}, it was formerly classified as a village shrine. It is designated a {{jalink|Kinpei-sha|Q119929592|Shirohei-sha}} by the Gifu Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines.

It is one of the candidate shrines (ronsa) for Kawashima Shrine of Kawashima in {{jalink|Haguri District|Q1032507}}, {{jalink|Owari Province|Q514506}}, listed in the {{jalink|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|Engishiki}} {{sfn|Kawashima Town|1982|pp=1179–1181}}<ref>The Owari-shi (a local gazetteer compiled by order of the {{jalink|Owari Domain|Q1062072}} in {{jalink|Tenpō|Q1369045}} 15 ({{jalink|1844|Q7633}})) records that “the Junior Third Rank Kawashima Tenjin of Haguri District listed in the Engishiki is the Shirahige Shrine of Kasada-jima Village.”</ref>. Other candidate shrines include {{jalink|Enoki Shrine (Kakamigahara)|Q134893091|Enoki Shrine}} in {{jalink|Kawashima Matsukura-chō|Q131870131}}, Kakamigahara City, and {{jalink|Kawashima Shrine (Kōnan)|Q11478285|Kawashima Shrine}} in Miyata-chō, {{jalink|Kōnan City|Q820496}}, {{jalink|Aichi Prefecture|Q80434}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{jalink|Sarutahiko|Q3090037|Sarutahiko-no-Mikoto}} (さるたひこのみこと)<ref name="案内"/>
* {{jalink|Amaterasu|Q455602}} (あまてらすおおみかみ)<ref name="案内"/>

=== History ===
[[File:Shirahige-jinja Kawashima ac (2).jpg|thumb|Main hall built atop high stone walls]]

The date of foundation is unknown. According to shrine tradition, it was established in the 10th year of the {{jalink|Mizunoe-Ne|Q904972}} era of Emperor {{jalink|Emperor Nintoku|Q313119}} following an imperial decree<ref>If taken as the 10th year of Emperor Nintoku’s reign, this would correspond to 322.</ref>, and a shrine building was constructed in the 4th year of the {{jalink|Kinoto-U|Q904791}} era of Emperor {{jalink|Emperor Ingyō|Q349258}} following another imperial decree<ref>If taken as the 4th year of Emperor Ingyō’s reign, this would correspond to 415.</ref><ref name="由緒">Explanatory signboard “History of Shirahige Shrine.”</ref>{{sfn|Kawashima Town|1982|p=1174}}.

In the 2nd year of {{jalink|Reiki|Q1373115}} (717), Hachiman Shrine was established as a subordinate shrine within the precincts<ref name="八幡神社">From the inscription on the monument marking the former site of Hachiman Shrine within the grounds of the Inaba District Gymnasium, Kakamigahara City.</ref>{{sfn|Kawashima Town|1982|p=1174}}.

In {{jalink|Tenshō|Q1145058}} 14 (1586), flooding of the {{jalink|Kiso River|Q779607}} washed away the shrine buildings. As a result of this flood, a new course of the Kiso River became the boundary between {{jalink|Owari Province|Q514506}} and {{jalink|Mino Province|Q864156}}, and this area changed from Haguri District, Owari Province, to {{jalink|Haguri District|Q11610214}}, Mino Province. The subordinate Hachiman Shrine was relocated to Majima in Haguri District (present-day {{jalink|Kakamigahara City|Q641491}} Kamiochi-chō, at the site of the {{jalink|Kakamigahara City Inaba District Gymnasium|Q109603254}})<ref name="八幡神社"/>. Thereafter, it was moved to its present location in Kasada, Haguri District, by {{jalink|Tsubouchi Toshisada|Q11425729}}, a {{jalink|Hatamoto|Q11501438}} of high rank stationed at {{jalink|Shinkano Jinya|Q11501438}} (former lord of {{jalink|Matsukura Castle (Owari Province)|Q11239240|Matsukura Castle}})<ref name="由緒"/>{{sfn|Kawashima Town|1982|p=1174}}. It was renamed Shirahige Myōjin and later changed to Shirahige Shrine.

During the Meiji period, it became a village shrine under the {{jalink|Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534}}. After World War II, it was designated a {{jalink|Kinpei-sha|Q119929592|Shirohei-sha}} by the Gifu Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines.

In 1999 (Heisei 11), the worship hall, norito hall, main hall, {{jalink|Heibei|Q124160302}}, and other structures were newly built, and Shinmei Shrine was enshrined together<ref>The former location was 1266 Koyabajima, Kasada-chō. It is now within {{jalink|Kasen Kankyō Rakuen|Q11553849}}.</ref>.

<gallery>
Shirahige-jinja Kawashima ac (4).jpg|Subordinate shrine
Shirahige-jinja Kawashima ac (3).jpg|Purification font
</gallery>

=== Subordinate shrines ===
Originally, there were two subordinate shrines: Kaijin Shrine and Akiba Shrine{{sfn|Kawashima Town|1982|p=1174}}. In 1996 (Heisei 8), nearby shrines were absorbed and incorporated as subordinate shrines.

* Kaijin Shrine (Deity: {{jalink|Watatsumi|Q1474187|Sokotsu Watatsumi-no-Kami}})<ref name="案内">From the on-site information board of “Shirahige Shrine.”</ref>
* Akiba Shrine (Deity: {{jalink|Kagutsuchi|Q1640658|Hi-no-Kagutsuchi-no-Kami}})<ref name="案内"/>
* Suijin Shrine (Deity: {{jalink|Amaterasu|Q455602}})<ref name="案内"/><ref>A shrine enshrined at the site of a levee breach caused by flooding. It was later relocated for river improvement and levee construction. In this area, Suijin Shrines sometimes enshrine deities other than {{jalink|Suijin|Q3137449}} (such as Amaterasu), possibly because they also serve the purpose of warding off flood damage.</ref>
* Inari Shrine (Deity: {{jalink|Ukanomitama|Q3080728|Ukanomitama-no-Kami}})<ref name="案内"/>
* Konpira Shrine (Deity: {{jalink|Ōkuninushi|Q276944|Ōkuninushi-no-Mikoto}})<ref name="案内"/>

=== Other ===
* {{jalink|Chūkonhi|Q11274518|Memorial monument for the war dead}}

=== Access ===
* From the “Kasada Higashiguchi” bus stop on the {{jalink|Kakamigahara City Fureai Bus|Q11412316}} Kawashima Line, an 8-minute walk.

