=== History ===
[[File:Shirahige-jinja Kawashima ac (2).jpg|thumb|Main hall built atop high stone walls]]

The date of foundation is unknown. According to shrine tradition, it was established in the 10th year of the {{ill|lt=Mizunoe-Ne|Q904972|WD=Q904972}} era of Emperor {{ill|lt=Emperor Nintoku|Q313119|WD=Q313119}} following an imperial decree<ref>If taken as the 10th year of Emperor Nintoku’s reign, this would correspond to 322.</ref>, and a shrine building was constructed in the 4th year of the {{ill|lt=Kinoto-U|Q904791|WD=Q904791}} era of Emperor {{ill|lt=Emperor Ingyō|Q349258|WD=Q349258}} following another imperial decree<ref>If taken as the 4th year of Emperor Ingyō’s reign, this would correspond to 415.</ref><ref name="由緒">Explanatory signboard “History of Shirahige Shrine.”</ref>{{sfn|Kawashima Town|1982|p=1174}}.

In the 2nd year of {{ill|lt=Reiki|Q1373115|WD=Q1373115}} (717), Hachiman Shrine was established as a subordinate shrine within the precincts<ref name="八幡神社">From the inscription on the monument marking the former site of Hachiman Shrine within the grounds of the Inaba District Gymnasium, Kakamigahara City.</ref>{{sfn|Kawashima Town|1982|p=1174}}.

In {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058}} 14 (1586), flooding of the {{ill|lt=Kiso River|Q779607|WD=Q779607}} washed away the shrine buildings. As a result of this flood, a new course of the Kiso River became the boundary between {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|WD=Q514506}} and {{ill|lt=Mino Province|Q864156|WD=Q864156}}, and this area changed from Haguri District, Owari Province, to {{ill|lt=Haguri District|Q11610214|WD=Q11610214}}, Mino Province. The subordinate Hachiman Shrine was relocated to Majima in Haguri District (present-day {{ill|lt=Kakamigahara City|Q641491|WD=Q641491}} Kamiochi-chō, at the site of the {{ill|lt=Kakamigahara City Inaba District Gymnasium|Q109603254|WD=Q109603254}})<ref name="八幡神社"/>. Thereafter, it was moved to its present location in Kasada, Haguri District, by {{ill|lt=Tsubouchi Toshisada|Q11425729|WD=Q11425729}}, a {{ill|lt=Hatamoto|Q11501438|WD=Q11501438}} of high rank stationed at {{ill|lt=Shinkano Jinya|Q11501438|WD=Q11501438}} (former lord of {{ill|lt=Matsukura Castle (Owari Province)|Q11239240|WD=Q11239240|lt=Matsukura Castle}})<ref name="由緒"/>{{sfn|Kawashima Town|1982|p=1174}}. It was renamed Shirahige Myōjin and later changed to Shirahige Shrine.

During the Meiji period, it became a village shrine under the {{ill|lt=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|WD=Q712534}}. After World War II, it was designated a {{ill|lt=Kinpei-sha|Q119929592|WD=Q119929592|lt=Shirohei-sha}} by the Gifu Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines.

In 1999 (Heisei 11), the worship hall, norito hall, main hall, {{ill|lt=Heibei|Q124160302|WD=Q124160302}}, and other structures were newly built, and Shinmei Shrine was enshrined together<ref>The former location was 1266 Koyabajima, Kasada-chō. It is now within {{ill|lt=Kasen Kankyō Rakuen|Q11553849|WD=Q11553849}}.</ref>.

